# CODEOWNERS — company-knowledge-brain
#
# The single repo rule, in plain English:
#
#   1. Default workflow is push direct to `main`. Anyone with write access
#      commits without ceremony.
#   2. The ONE exception is `canon/` — every change to that folder must go
#      through a pull request, and the owner (@your-github-handle) is the reviewer.
#
# This file enforces the second half via auto-review-request: when a PR
# touches `canon/**`, GitHub auto-requests the owner as a required
# reviewer. The first half is enforced by NOT setting branch protection
# on `main` for non-canon paths.
#
# Bypass paths are protected:
#   - `/.github/CODEOWNERS` itself (this file): editing it would let
#     someone remove the owner from the canon route. Owner-only.
#   - `/.github/workflows/`: the direct-push guard lives here. Owner-only.
#
# Technological note (limitation of the GitHub free plan):
#   - On the **free** plan a **private** repo does not include Rulesets or
#     Branch Protection. Real server-side blocking of direct pushes to
#     `canon/**` is NOT available until the repo upgrades to GitHub Pro,
#     GitHub Team, or is made public.
#   - As a workaround, `.github/workflows/canon-direct-push-guard.yml`
#     runs on every push to `main` and fails the workflow if a commit
#     modifies `canon/**` without coming from a merged PR. This is
#     REACTIVE enforcement (the push happens, the check fails after) —
#     not preventive. The convention does the rest.
#
# CODEOWNERS syntax: gitignore-style globs; last-matching-line wins.
#
# SETUP: replace @your-github-handle below with the repo owner's GitHub
# handle (or a team like @your-org/leads).

# ─── Default: no owner required ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# By design — push direct to `main` works for everyone with write access.
# Anything not matched below has NO required reviewer.

# ─── canon/ — company truth, PR-only, owner-reviewed ────────────────────────
# Every change here auto-requests the owner as required reviewer.
/canon/                        @your-github-handle

# ─── Bypass-protection — owner-only ─────────────────────────────────────────
# Editing CODEOWNERS or the enforcement workflow would let someone bypass
# the canon/ rule. So both are owner-protected.
/.github/CODEOWNERS            @your-github-handle
/.github/workflows/            @your-github-handle
